  "prompt": "What is transactional pricing?",
  "response": "Transactional pricing is a pricing strategy where the price of a product or service is determined based on the specific details and circumstances of each individual transaction. Key characteristics include:\n\n1. Flexibility\n- Prices can vary depending on different factors\n- Tailored to specific customer, market, or transaction conditions\n\n2. Factors influencing price\n- Volume of purchase\n- Customer relationship\n- Market demand\n- Timing of transaction\n- Negotiation dynamics\n- Competitive landscape\n\n3. Common applications\n- B2B (business-to-business) sales\n- Complex or customized product/service offerings\n- Industries with high variability in transaction details\n\n4. Advantages\n- Allows for dynamic pricing\n- Can maximize revenue potential\n- Enables personalized pricing strategies\n- Adapts to market changes quickly\n\n5. Disadvantages\n- Can be complex to manage\n- Potential perception of unfairness\n- Requires sophisticated pricing systems\n- May create pricing inconsistencies\n\n6. Examples\n- Wholesale pricing\n- Volume discounts\n- Negotiated contract pricing\n- Real-time market pricing\n\nTransactional pricing differs from fixed pricing, where prices remain consistent across all transactions, by offering more adaptability and customization.",
